    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<!-- excerpt --><h2 id="Summary"><a href="#Summary" class="headerlink" title="Summary"></a>Summary</h2><p>The first part of this book reviews the graphical practice of the two centuries, and the second part provides a language for discussing graphics and a practical theory of data graphics. It’s concerned both with design and with statistics, but it is also about how to communicate information through words, numbers, and pictures.</p><h2 id="Part-1-Graphical-Practice"><a href="#Part-1-Graphical-Practice" class="headerlink" title="Part 1: Graphical Practice"></a>Part 1: Graphical Practice</h2><p><strong>Keywords</strong>: clarity, precision, and efficiency</p><h3 id="One-varaible-time"><a href="#One-varaible-time" class="headerlink" title="[One varaible: time]"></a>[One varaible: time]</h3><p>Great graphical design:<br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/pw/ACtC-3cgMV3IrFVQ7v5P4J0eVWo4IdzMSehBphgdyTyqGL1viQcC0e7VdtPzqjkFjer2B9wQLIQkQ9rFcRZzMfaDrg7GWZ9XBBSCbDqA-20zIL7T0MuY-BhedocQNsUVItfj97DuD1YgtDR6mJngPO0oLIc=w551-h915-no?authuser=0" width="400px" height="450px"></p><ol><li>horizontal line: length of stop at a station.  </li><li>The stations are seperate in proportion to their actual distance apart</li><li>slope refelcts the speed of the train</li></ol><p><strong>[Multivariable]</strong><br>bring in additional variabeles to eplain the transformed and improved series at the bottom<br>eg: relational graph<br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/pw/ACtC-3d4njaH6RYWyvlYzeOwQEqtDa2LKtWF_AukwSU4hnhgCU0uJKI9qAbfsH-QBGyZmnZwLAHx8mL9wWdjdQ5ClbtN0GXlbrWVcI6Ol_XwERIfMr_naSHtpvoiL2G9nohqGoTjZ4jrMq98YzChoQv39-A=w847-h707-no?authuser=0" widt="400" height="400"></p><p><strong>[Graph integrity]</strong><br>The visual representation of the data must be consistent with the numerical representation.<br>Lie Factor = size of effect shown in graphic / size of effect in data</p><p>An extreme example:<br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/pw/ACtC-3c5Z21nraOvn0VCvpRpd-ZVbTv4bJrh-DhanJYS6TrcxFEmSnXm1jMJoyO5MXWr5aDbvB3N1sSm4M1wg1x1Xy1jUJ9_M2iYEXtHE4xBOheh2J3BuH5D168pIvSlprG24NSMvNyhJXBD8xyvTe6SRT8=w1088-h522-no?authuser=0" width="600" height="300"><br>The magnitude of the change from 1978 to 1985 as shown in the graph is 783%, while the numerical change is 53%. Therefore the Lie Factor = 783/53 = 14.8, which is too big.</p><p>Firstly, a graph should display data variaion, not design variation. For example, a chaning of unit at the end is a design vatiation. In time-series displays of money, deflated and standardlized units of monetary measurementt are nearly always better than nominal units.</p><p>Secondly, using two varying dimensions to show one-dimensional data is a week and inefficient technique.<br>The number of variable dimensions depicted should not exceed the number of dimensions in the data.<br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/pw/ACtC-3e0PAmgUmCqH4bhAapC64iqBrYgoaYLuQsObrTqz3-Z5UYixoCBqeuE_Mte-NH_c6x1WAygLjMj5KIzhgcfz2yWRR43LGHJIV1QAUuaw-I3c4UrFPr_pwjuMUoxoEZsc5QWrHJttc7D5-E3q1tWIcA=w609-h900-no?authuser=0" width="400" height="350"><br>If the area of the dollar is accureately reflected, then the 1978 dollar should be about twice as big as that shown.</p><p>Thirdly, graphics need to preserve the context of data. Different range of data chosen can result in completely different intepretations.<br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/pw/ACtC-3dIzYV8usV4lWbCJECVETKj4WB4AlxSf53feRgBjM5Wpc7ZK3DZ0bAU0IAo65dWc_-qSmKcrEe037toRi0szernAXPz-k82pXdAltTaJGPEWJAb4mKwFhXZjVy0jS_rZR29-fdjUeSs18JOiukD6wo=w699-h810-no?authuser=0" width="300" height="300"></p><h2 id="Part-2-Theory-of-Data-Graphics"><a href="#Part-2-Theory-of-Data-Graphics" class="headerlink" title="Part 2: Theory of Data Graphics"></a>Part 2: Theory of Data Graphics</h2><p><strong>Data-Ink</strong><br>A large share of ink should present data information.<br>Data-ink ratio = data-ink / total ink used to print the graphc.</p><p>An example of a graph whose ink is devoted mostly to non-data info:<br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/IKJK1A6Z9GBpQ5tpTUGiOtFsxi_lFZbAyvUZrcVodB-I_5c4FCbhXQAYseG2ff26BdKBQ7RuvzIWleQ2zxOmCNpBtyXssNdJhAZE61qysLWZ64EOJNEyiSn1fMWTaQ7d5hz9D13uBcwXNqX-GYGKbLYE8H5F33gGMJmnsCvLQXdJ6IsH-cQNHInSQStU1cWaBDqXU7j5ecq5h86pZee4xisWRzxMlzAnvaQQ5x383vmiklqyavMeud2thBTEyRrhwEd3MdkNrDDu_baXixTNd54SKlL38IBQGvmlAUzi35rzizn6Fddp_jmaFsJ4KvyQyY6lYclvquYYCuKCaw9qmL385_3ridV0VK-ro-frj74ITzx67MxnfkoVHCvJqFVatoZrzhmcN_SiqTd3VhS8RNCbnyr9xI-b0PYgrAVU3M1meDodsv_GUdryl4WNsHPhcbVeXLuxYpY-sOlQocQqaT2NAOzLsjkgjXtaIYFtWhG9GLts4jIo-5f48vjmPIAxsses11PgYy5Upje4gxsrzJl7--CwppK3XkHBHCr65VERA5932Uz5LnzepVf4J46CVxJMYFP94MWi1bWtSKLngHQHWcvXWPO7xPn51OYbaH0Fhhpuz8D_7VFsXQNKjslMXJbZnShgnrRXkxFLi2mAUZCA5L1hWa6oGcAU3-fzi8zLvsyxBALEIN6RxU4G=w767-h812-no?authuser=0" width="300px" height="400px"></p><p>As a result, the grid sea overwhelms the numbers.</p><p>In order to maximize the data-ink ratio, there are two erasing principles:</p><ol><li><p>Erase non-data-ink within reason</p></li><li><p>Remove redundant data-ink within reason<br>For symmetrical data such as box plot and open bar, it’s enough to present the left half.</p><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/Pjqm-q70qP6wx89Q9sjVQy84cpUROCpeX5711Vg9EC-4N7UpnqvF77LqHl5y1Q_x4MKQE5bQuV8FXmreE5rTiYXIN0KB6SApz8dB3x-Q3-8DkpPwWi4LKMt9gPLpCunOElnnK1EUD7LI8HnyWHFxgrsP5K5MmB_n5QMJQP2BKg5i0qoCRxrb9QKJVd2mXEljCXlWJrDGlLUZ0FOpWkiOULGeQ_PVuhZpGUtbMnKR2C7CWlmXuU3M7YNdFJWELw8SgB0KU0d4orXoDmfiana4gkV30S_wvZh9LMoRbre0Q5D5VLyVaFDnko41K7zqBFfYu7JINIYaYnrZSLO0fedZ2kZW1jrmOkcexZ-1wxoxf_ao5lroe5NkOG_qxpCbFvNFz1-WFRkRJn0tF-70K1DAdJX7Ew19PENwU2hJs04JHL7y6Qe3Dj3JKFmLOu4ZeSuDhawiHnYTr4TVQ7pHcHoFNdNrpvxGov12TjQeoDdTHEC8UNeMFYKgs6JHysHP6yOYajNB5XbRAKcd0v8XijegP_7DU4IxnbJOuCBVyXy6-LpSCLpRMhInSkyGO9qJFOQjS8US1Hrk2fJBMozwaW0k85d7_3GFjcHxIlNaJXV4lgB8wazF07LDKyr5FGmP8frOsUlYgTOgVE22ozz3NPC_f40dm5s2ugFxJhPJLvrTkMoyXawqUq3D53Wsqcvl=w1110-h600-no?authuser=0" width = "400px" hei